Have a scheduled job to delete expired keys (requirement in our enterprise environment) and this works fine as an event listener where StashAuthenticationContext has a valid user, but for scheduled jobs this returns null, causing the DefaultSshKeyService to reject the call to update/remove the key in question.

{code}
public boolean canEditSshKeyForUser(@Nonnull StashUser user)
  {
    Preconditions.checkNotNull(user, "user");
    
    StashUser currentUser = this.authenticationContext.getCurrentUser();
    if ((currentUser != null) && (user.getId().equals(currentUser.getId()))) {
      return true;
    }
    if (this.permissionService.hasGlobalPermission(user, Permission.SYS_ADMIN)) {
      return this.permissionService.hasGlobalPermission(Permission.SYS_ADMIN);
    }
    if (user.getType() == UserType.NORMAL) {
      return this.permissionService.hasGlobalPermission(Permission.ADMIN);
    }
    return this.permissionService.hasAnyUserPermission(Permission.REPO_ADMIN);
  }{code}


I would argue that in order to make the system more extensible this validation should be handled at a higher level, or allow means for a plugin (especially scheduled jobs) to set a mock context before calling the SshKeyService.
